JQuery Notes

Everything you can do on html/css, you can also do it on JS.

If you want to create a new element inside a variable to include in the html you have to use the the alligators signs.
eg. $(<'li'>). --- this is going to create a new element to the DOM
eg. $('li'). --- This selects the id li

    $('<div>') // create a div element
    $('<p>') // creates a new p elemnt
    $('<button>') // creates a new button elemnt

    $('p') // select all p elements from the DOM
    $('button') // selects all button elements from the DOM

    $('.class-name') // selects all elements from the DOM that have class name: "class-name"
    $('.red') // selects all elements from the DOM that have class name: "red"

    $('#drink-list') // selects THE FIRST ELEMENT who has ID "drink-list"

Momento de confusion para explicar la funcion Ready
Always, include $(document).ready(function()

SCOPES example from Josh

  var globalVar = 'josh';
  function outer() {
    var outerVar = 'outer';
    
    function inner1() {
      var inner1Var = 'inner1';
      
      function inner2() {
        var inner2Var = 'inner2';
        
        function inner3() {
          var inner3Var = 'inner3';
          
          function inner4() {
            var inner4Var = 'inner4';
          }

          console.log(inner4());
        }
      }
    }
  }

